<TITLE> Modi to strengthen BJP: poll </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Wed Apr 1,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. (Items are from own sources unless stated.) Narendra Modi, chief minister of Gujarat, will strengthen the Bharatiya Janata Party's (BJP) influence in the region and is also a favourite among 79 percent of the people for development work, according to a poll by a news channel. At least 45 percent of the people want Modi as chief minister, despite the Supreme Court criticising him for one of India's worst religious riots in 2002. Gujarat will elect 26 lawmakers in the upcoming election and is a key state for the BJP. (NDTV) Despite a number of allies deserting the Congress party, days before the general election, the party is still hopeful of putting its house in order. Prime Minister Manmohan Singh said most parties are still with the Congress and more will support them after the election. (The Indian Express) A communist leader could be the next prime minister of India, if the left succeeds in forming a non-Congress, non-BJP government. The communists will take a tactical decision when it comes to joining a government and was keeping its options open. (Hindustan Times) Bollywood star Sanjay Dutt's attempts to enter politics were stopped by Supreme Court after police objected his plea to stay his conviction in the 1993 Mumbai blast case. (Hindustan Times) Varun Gandhi, a BJP candidate and the great-grandson of the country's first prime minister was moved to a high security jail, amid reports that Muslim gangsters were planning to kill him. Gandhi, a BJP candidate from Uttar Pradesh was taken into custody at the weekend and booked under the National Security Act for making inflammatory comments against Muslims.
